<Base
  title="The Tyrer Framework | Carrados | Charli-Jo Tyrer"
  description="The Tyrer Framework explains accessibility as information integrity, visual dominance, information casualties and a path towards perceptual sovereignty."
>
  <h1>The Tyrer Framework</h1>
  <p class="site-intro">Accessibility as information integrity.</p>
  <p>The Tyrer Framework is a theoretical model that treats accessibility as a property of information systems rather than an accommodation for particular users.</p>

  <section aria-labelledby="tyrers-law">
    <h2 id="tyrers-law">Tyrer's Law</h2>
    <p>Open technological systems naturally drift towards visual dominance because most designers think visually. As systems become richer, meaning is increasingly encoded in visual form and becomes unavailable to observers using other sensory channels.</p>
    <p>This produces information casualties: moments where relevant information fails to reach an observer in time to support perception, action or participation. These failures are not isolated mistakes or lapses in goodwill. They are predictable consequences of how technology evolves when visual presentation becomes the authoritative source of meaning.</p>
  </section>

  <section aria-labelledby="accessibility-scale">
    <h2 id="accessibility-scale">The Tyrer Accessibility Scale</h2>
    <p>The Tyrer Accessibility Scale measures progress by the proportion of environmental information available to every observer, regardless of sensory modality.</p>
    <p>It traces a path from visually dominant systems through structured semantic information and machine-readable environments towards Perceptual Sovereignty: a condition in which relevant environmental information can reach every observer and the probability of information casualties approaches zero.</p>
  </section>

  <section aria-labelledby="generative-accessibility">
    <h2 id="generative-accessibility">From Classical to Generative Accessibility</h2>
    <p>Classical Accessibility generally translates or adapts a visual original after it has been made. Generative Accessibility begins with shared semantic information and produces native renderings for different people, interfaces and technologies.</p>
    <p>In this model, a screen-reader experience, voice interface or agent-facing representation is not a reduced version of a visual design. It is a first-class rendering of the same authoritative meaning.</p>
  </section>

  <section aria-labelledby="tyrer-doctrine">
    <h2 id="tyrer-doctrine">The Tyrer Doctrine</h2>
    <p>No critical environmental information should ever exist in only a single sensory channel.</p>
    <p>The doctrine frames accessibility as engineering and infrastructure. Artificial intelligence offers the first genuine opportunity to weaken the structural drift described by Tyrer's Law by allowing interfaces to be generated from shared semantic information rather than copied from a visual original.</p>
  </section>

